==English==

===Etymology===
15th Century, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|absolvere||to set free, to absolve|lang=la}}, from {{term|ab-|lang=la}} + {{term|solvere||to loose|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əbˈzɒlv/}}
* {{audio|en-us-absolve.ogg|Audio (US)}}
{{rfp|US?}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|absolv|ing}}

# {{transitive}} To [[set free]], [[release]] or [[discharge]] (from [[obligation]]s, [[debt]]s, [[responsibility]] etc.).
#: ''You will '''absolve''' a subject from his allegiance.''
#* {{quote-book|year=1855|author=[[w:Thomas Babington Macaulay|Thomas Babington Macaulay]]|title=The History of England from the Accession of James II|volume=III|chapter-number=XIV}}
#*: Halifax was '''absolved''' by a majority of fourteen.
# {{transitive}} To [[pronounce]] [[free]] from or give [[absolution]] for a [[penalty]], [[blame]], [[sin]] or [[guilt]].
# {{transitive|theology}} To pronounce free or give [[absolution]] from [[sin]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1782|author=[[w:Edward Gibbon|Edward Gibbon]]|title=History Of The Decline And Fall Of The Roman Empire|volume=VI|chapter-number=LXVII}}
#*: In his name I '''absolve''' your perjury and sanctify your arms.
# {{transitive|obsolete}} To [[finish]]; to [[accomplish]].
#* {{RQ:Milton Lost|VII}}, line 94
#*: and the work begun, how soon / '''Absolv’d''',
# {{transitive|obsolete}} To [[resolve]] or [[explain]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1646|author=[[w:Thomas Browne|Sir Thomas Browne]]|title=[[w:Pseudodoxia Epidemica|Pseudodoxia Epidemica]]|chapter-number=VI|page=x|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/pseudodoxia/pseudodoxia.shtml}}
#*: We shall not '''absolve''' the doubt.

